{{other people}} '''Jakob Aall Ottesen Larsen''' (March 1, 1888 – September 2, 1974) was an American [[classics|classical scholar]]. He was known principally for his research on the political status of [[Ancient Greece]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://lichen.csd.sc.edu/dbcs/index.php?page=person&id=668 |title= Larsen, Jakob Aall Ottesen |publisher= Database of Classical Scholarship |author= Michael P. McHugh |date= |accessdate= January 1, 2016}}</ref>
==Biography== Jakob Aall Ottesen Larsen was born in [[Decorah, Iowa]]. He was the son of [[Peter Laurentius Larsen]], founding president of [[Luther College (Iowa)|Luther College]], and his second wife Ingeborg Astrup (1846-1923)<ref>[[Ward W. Briggs]] Jr.: [https://www.questia.com/read/26205704/biographical-dictionary-of-north-american-classicists Biographical Dictionary of North American Classicists] (paywall) via Questia.com. Retrieved 8 September 2013</ref> He received a BA from Luther College in 1908 and MA from [[Yale University|Yale]] in 1911. In 1914, he earned a [[Rhodes scholarship]]. He studied at [[Oxford University]] from 1914–1920. In 1928, Larsen received his Ph.D. from [[Harvard University|Harvard]]. The [[University of Vermont]] awarded him the LL.D. in 1953, and Luther College presented him with his D.Litt. in 1961.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://oxfordindex.oup.com/view/10.1093/anb/9780198606697.article.2001462 |title= Larsen, Jakob Aall Ottesen |publisher= Oxford Index |date= February 2000 |accessdate= January 1, 2016}}</ref>
Larsen worked as an Assistant Professor of History at the [[University of Washington]] from 1921 to 1926. From 1926 through 1929, he served in the same capacity at [[Ohio State University]]. He was promoted to Associate Professor and continued in that capacity at Ohio State University until 1930. In 1930–1943 he served as an Associate Professor of History at the [[University of Chicago]], then as a Professor (1943–1953, and as a Professor Emeritus from 1953 to 1971. Professor Larsen was the managing editor of ''Classical Philology'' from 1939 to 1951. From 1951 to 1952 he was chairman of the [[American Philological Association]]. He served as the [[Peder Sather|Sather]] Professor of Classics at the [[University of California]]-Berkeley in 1954 and as Visiting Professor of History at [[Rutgers University]] in 1956 and 1957. He was also Visiting Professor of History at the [[University of Texas]] in 1960 and at the [[University of Missouri]] from 1960 to 1971. <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.classics.berkeley.edu/people/sather/history |title= A Brief History of the Sather Professorship |publisher= University of California ~ Berkeley |author= Joseph Fontenrose |date= 1982 |accessdate= January 1, 2016}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.classics.berkeley.edu/people/sather/list |title= Past and Future Sather Professors |publisher= University of California ~ Berkeley |accessdate= January 1, 2016}}</ref>
==Personal life== He was married to Clarice (Grindeland) Larsen (1886-1974). He died during 1974 in [[Columbia, Missouri]]. Both he and his wife were buried in the Lutheran Cemetery [[Winneshiek County, Iowa]]. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://nordic.luther.edu/?p=creators/creator&id=182 |title= Larsen, J. A. O. (1888-1974) |publisher= Nordic, Norwegian-American Digital Library |accessdate= January 1, 2016}}</ref>
==Works== * ''Representative Government in Greek and Roman History'', 1955 ([[American Philological Association]]'s C.J. Goodwin Award of Merit, 1957) * ''Greek Federal States: Their Institutions and History'', 1968
==Further reading== * "Jakob A.O. Larsen: [Obituary]", ''Classical Philology'', Vol.&nbsp;70, No.&nbsp;2. (Apr., 1975), p.&nbsp;126. * Mullet, Charles F. "[Jakob Larsen: Obituary]", ''The American Historical Review'', Vol.&nbsp;80, No.&nbsp;3. (Jun., 1975), pp.&nbsp;746–748.
