[[File:Mike Filey, prior to a ceremony at the Distillery Loop, 2016 06 18 (27751979955) (cropped).jpg|thumb|Mike Filey, 2016]]
'''Mike Filey''' (born 1941) is a Canadian historian, journalist and author. He was awarded the Jean Hibbert Memorial Award in 2009 for promoting the city of [[Toronto]] and its history.

==Early life==
Born in 1941 in [[Toronto]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.harbourfrontcentre.com/whatson/today.cfm?id=5917&festival_id=180 |title=Lecture: Mike Filey |website=Harbourfront Centre |access-date=June 4, 2018}}</ref> Filey attended high school at [[North Toronto Collegiate Institute ]] and earned a degree in chemical technology from [[Ryerson Polytechnical Institute]].<ref name="EHS">{{Cite web | url = http://www.etobicokehistorical.com/mike-filey.html | title = Mike Filey - 2009 Recipient of The Jean Hibbert Memorial Award | website = Etobicoke Historical Society | access-date = June 4, 2018 | quote = However, over 25 years ago now, Mike turned his interests to his true vocation – researching, documenting and speaking about Toronto's history. }}</ref><ref name="TBI">{{Cite web |url=http://www.intelligencer.ca/author/mike-filey |title=Mike Filey |website=The Belleville Intelligencer |access-date=June 4, 2018}}</ref>

As a child Filey's family lived on [[Bathurst Street, Toronto|Bathurst Street]], just south of the iconic [[Honest Ed's]].<ref name=TorontoSun2018-11-17/>

==Career==
Filey began his career at what is now the [[Ontario Ministry of the Environment]], working there for nine years. He then worked for five years at the [[Canadian National Exhibition]] and four years at [[Canada's Wonderland]].<ref name="EHS" />

In 1972, he was an organizer of Heritage Toronto, a citizen's group interested in Toronto's history.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/46178537/?terms=%2522Mike%252BFiley%2522%252BToronto |title=Three city halls still stand in Toronto|date=November 27, 1972| page=24 |newspaper= The Ottawa Journal  |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Since 1975, he has written the column, ''The Way We Were'' for the [[Toronto Sun]]. He has written more than two dozen books about the history of Toronto. Among the topics covered are [[Toronto Transit Commission]] (TTC), books with old photographs, and nine books of ''Toronto Sketches''. He also has a radio show on [[CFZM|New AM 740]].<ref name="EHS" /> His guided walks include topics such as ''Toronto, Then and Now''.<ref name="EHS" />

According to his friend Alan Parker, another columnist at the ''[[Toronto Sun]]'', Filey is known as ''"Toronto’s best-known historian"''.<ref name=TorontoSun2008-11-09/>

==Personal life==
He and his wife, Yarmila, live in [[Willowdale, Toronto]].<ref name="TBI" />

